The paper deals with the problem of determining market clearing prices in a general linear Arrow-Debreu market, which is a problem in computational game theory (cs.GT). The algorithm presented in the paper is combinatorial in nature and involves several new ideas, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the sub-categories of combinatorics (cs.DM) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the hardness of the problem and identifies hard instances, which could be of interest to researchers in computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the problem of market clearing prices is closely related to the field of microeconomics and mechanism design, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of electronic commerce (cs.EC).
